Tidyverse: tidyr

Bernard Ade

tidyr is a package that reshapes the layout of a dataset so that it’s suitable for analysis. Hadley Wickham the creator of tidyr wrote a paper that elaborates on the principals of tidy data. You can read that paper here, Tidy Paper - Hadley Wickham. My goal in this post is to briefly highlight the principals of tidy data and demonstate proof of concept.

The principals that governs transforming a messy dataset to a tidy dataset is defined as such:

  1. Each variable must form a column.
  2. Each observation must form a row.
  3. Each type of observational unit must form a table.
library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)

Dataset

The dataset below exemplifies an untidy dataset unsuitable for analysis. The columns are wide, the variables do not form a column and each observation does not form a row. Lets tidy this dataset.

messy_data = read.csv("life_expectancy.csv")
messy_data

For some odd reason, the life expectancy dataset above includes the letter X in front of each year, lets get rid of it.

names(messy_data) = c("Country.Name", "Country.Code", 1960:2013)
messy_data

Gather

When we run the gather function, R will return a dataset in a long format. With each variable forming it’s own row, we now have a tidy dataset.

tidy_data = gather(messy_data, "year", "n", 3:56)
tidy_data

Spread

Also in the tidy package is the spread function which generates multiple columns. We can reverse what we did with the gather function using the spread function.

spread_tidy_data = spread(tidy_data, "year", n)
spread_tidy_data

Unite

The unite function unites values in columns into a single column. Lets combine country name and code into a single column.

unite_tidy_data = unite(tidy_data, "Country_name_code", Country.Name, Country.Code, sep = "-")
unite_tidy_data

separate(unite_tidy_data, Country_name_code, c("Country.Name", "Country.Code"), sep = "-")

Lets filter rows down to 2013 and display quick bar plot.

tidy_data_2013 = 
  tidy_data %>%
  filter(year == 2013)
tidy_data_2013
library(highcharter)
highchart()%>%
  hc_chart(type = "column", colorByPoint = TRUE) %>%
  hc_title(text = "2013 World Life Expectancy Rate") %>%
  hc_xAxis(categories = tidy_data_2013$Country.Name) %>%
  hc_add_series(name = "Country", data = tidy_data_2013$n)
